Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil and lightly oil (or coat with nonstick cooking spray). Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings).

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion; cook for ~{3%minutes}.

Add @ground beef{10%oz}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through and onion is softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}, @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit}, and @water{1/3%cup}. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn off heat.

> Swap in turkey or beef for pork.

Meanwhile, drizzle @flour tortillas{6} with @olive oil{1%tbsp}; brush or rub to completely coat on both sides.

Place tortillas on a clean work surface. Once pork filling is done, add a heaping ¼ cup filling to one side of each tortilla, then sprinkle each with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create taquitos. Place, seam sides down, on prepared #baking sheet{}. 

> Make sure the taquitos are snug on the sheet—this will prevent them from unrolling.

Bake on middle rack until golden brown and crispy, ~{8-12%minutes}.

While taquitos bake, finely dice @tomato{1}. Zest and quarter @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, minced onion, half the lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice. Season with @salt{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @guacamole{4%tbsp}, @sour cream{3%tbsp}, remaining lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice. Season with salt and @pepper{}.

Divide taquitos between plates. Top with pico de gallo, creamy guacamole, and @hot sauce{1%tsp}. Serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.